ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book presents a unique rethinking of G. W. F. Hegel's philosophy from unusual and controversial perspectives in order to liberate new energies from his philosophy. The role Hegel ascribes to women in the shaping of society and family, the reconstruction of his anthropological and psychological perspective, his approach to human nature, the relationship between mental illness and social disease, the role of the unconscious, and the relevance of intercultural and interreligious pathways: All these themes reveal new and inspiring aspects of Hegel’s thought for our time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aGender. 4aHegel. 4aInterkulturelle Studien. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aHegel.  across-cultural Studies.  agender.  aunconscious.1 aAchella, Stefania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAchella, Stefania, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAndreozzi, Giovanni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAngelucci, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnzalone, Mariafilomena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaptist, Gabriella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaptist, Gabriella, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBattistoni, Giulia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBella, Giuseppa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelmonte, Carmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBienenstock, Myriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonito Oliva, Rossella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov